Seaborn: matplotlib for the masses

An interesting new addition to the python scientific libraries is Seaborn; this graphical library is built on top of matplotlib, providing interesting styles and plotting routines.

The library is a mixture of handy style functions, handy and better plots, and even analysis tools.

# Read some example data
x = [float(l.strip().split()[0]) for l in open('test.tsv')]
y = [float(l.strip().split()[1]) for l in open('test.tsv')]

def logistic(x, A=404.45, u=10.73, d=11.96, v=0.1, y0=-40.64):
    '''
    Logistic growth model
    Taken from: "Modeling of the bacterial growth curve."
                (Zwietering et al., 1990)
                PMID: 16348228
    '''
    y = (A / (1 + np.exp( ( ((4 * u)/A) * (d - x) ) + 2 ))) + y0
    return y

def gompertz(x, A=404.45, u=10.73, d=11.96, v=0.1, y0=-10.64):
    '''
    Gompertz growth model
    Taken from: "Modeling of the bacterial growth curve."
                (Zwietering et al., 1990)
                PMID: 16348228
    '''
    y = (A * np.exp( -np.exp( (((u * np.e)/A) * (d - x)) + 1 ) ) ) + y0
    return y

def richards(x, A=404.45, u=12.73, d=11.96, v=1, y0=-30.64):
    '''
    Richards growth model
    (equivalent to Stannard)
    Taken from: "Modeling of the bacterial growth curve."
                (Zwietering et al., 1990)
                PMID: 16348228
    '''
    y = (A * pow(1 + (v + (np.exp(1 + v) * np.exp( (u/A) * (1 + v) * (1 + (1/v)) * (d - x) ) ) ),-(1/v))) + y0
    return y
In [4]: 
def plot_curves(x, y):
    x1 = np.linspace(0, max(x), 1000)

    plt.plot(x,
             y,
             '+r',
             lw=2,
             label='Original data')

    plt.plot(x1,
             logistic(x1),
             '-b',
             lw=2,
             alpha=0.6,
             label='Logistic fit')

    plt.plot(x1,
             gompertz(x1),
             '-g',
             lw=2,
             alpha=0.6,
             label='Gompertz fit')

    plt.plot(x1,
             richards(x1),
             '-y',
             lw=2,
             alpha=0.6,
             label='Richards fit')

    plt.xlabel('Time (h)')
    plt.ylabel('Signal (units)')

    plt.legend(loc='best')

Styles as context managers

Please note that the subplot function must be inside the context manager

In [7]: 
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 10))

with sns.axes_style('darkgrid'):
    plt.subplot(2, 2, 1)
    plot_curves(x, y)
plt.title('darkgrid')

with sns.axes_style('whitegrid'):
    plt.subplot(2, 2, 2)
    plot_curves(x, y)
plt.title('whitegrid')

with sns.axes_style('white'):
    plt.subplot(2, 2, 3)
    plot_curves(x, y)
plt.title('white')

with sns.axes_style('dark'):
    plt.subplot(2, 2, 4)
    plot_curves(x, y)
plt.title('dark')

Heatmaps and clustermaps

A recent addition to seaborn are heatmaps and clustermaps; heatmaps were kind of ok with matplotlib, but a dendrogram clustering required extensive knowledge of scipy and lots of creativity.
